                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Oct. 19 (PTI): The Rajiv Gandhi Foundation headed by Sonia Gandhi is not liable to answer queries under the RTI Act as it does not fulfil the criteria of a public authority, the Central Information Commission has held.          
	The foundation, which runs a number of welfare projects, was established in 1991 to promote the former Prime Ministers ideals. To qualify for public authority, an entity should be owned, controlled or substantially financed, directly or indirectly, by the government, CIC has said.                   
	 Raipur (PTI): Four persons were arrested on Tuesday for spraying black ink at Union minister of state for parliamentary affairs V. Narayanasamy. He was in Raipur for a state Congress committee meeting.                   
	 Kanpur (PTI): A schoolteacher was shot dead on Tuesday allegedly by two persons when he was going to a temple at a village in Kanpur. Agitated over the death of Pankaj Singh, an irate mob set on fire a police station and damaged police vehicles in the Ghatampur area near Kanpur.                   
	 Washington (PTI): An Indian-American academic and IIT Madras alumnus, Subra Suresh, has been sworn in as director of the National Science Foundation, the top US science body that leads scientific research in America.                  
	 Bangalore (PTI): The Karnataka government will recruit 8,000 schoolteachers by March 2011 to fill vacancies. The posts had fallen vacant as many teachers had retired, minister for primary and secondary education Vishveshwara Hegde Kageri said on Tuesday.                  
	 Salem (PTI): A truck driver and cleaner on their way back to Namakkal after selling eggs worth Rs 3.39 lakh in Bangalore were robbed of the cash by a four member gang near Salem in Tamil Nadu on Tuesday, police said. The driver stopped after two women flashed torchlights. Then two others emerged and tied the driver and his helper to a tree before escaping with the cash.
                                                                                                                                              
